Promise becomes resolved only when you call the `resolve` callback. If promise was not resolved or rejected it remains in the `pending` state forever.

`Await` keyword is used to actually &quot;wait until promise resolves&quot; and it never happens in your example.

Your function `test` expects some function to execute when timeout passes. When you pass `resolve` as an argument of the `test` function it will be called after timeout, promise become resolved and you see the console logs.

